INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

Late. One work lamp. DUTCH alone at the plywood table with the build drawings, his binder, and a slide rule.

He counts scrubber cartridges on the parts shelf against a line in the drawing. Counts again. Sits down slow.

He works the slide rule. Checks the drawing's spare-cartridge rack, four slots, not one, against the swap interval called out in his own notes. Writes a figure. Works it again from the other direction, and writes the same figure, and boxes it, twice.

INSERT — THE PAD: CARTRIDGE RACK, 4 SPARES/UNIT. SWAP EVERY ~15 HRS. = 4 SWAPS, FULL TRANSIT.

Dutch looks at the boxed line a long time. Then he gets up, crosses to crate number one, finished, gleaming under the tarp, pulls the tarp off, undogs the lid, and opens it.

Inside is a molded couch with a head cradle and restraint webbing, shaped exactly like a man.

Dutch stands there looking into it a long time, one hand on the lid.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - THE NEXT EVENING

All of them: the four olds, Joss, Tito, and MACK, called in. The build drawing lies on the plywood table with Dutch's pad on top of it, the boxed figure facing up.

DUTCH:
I told this room the fabric needs to ride flat. Stable. Purged, so the dye doesn't go on the way down. I believed my own math on that.
(beat, tapping the rack detail)
But this — four spare cartridges, swapped every fifteen hours or so — that's not a purge charge. You seal a purge charge once and leave it alone. Something that needs swapping on a schedule is using it up. There's only one thing on this crate that uses up air.

He lets that sit.

DUTCH:
There is no version of this drawing where nobody's inside it.

He turns the drawing around to face Mack.

DUTCH:
It's a life-support system with a museum sticker on it. I should know. I wrote it. And I talked myself out of my own spec sheet.

He lets that sit one beat.

DUTCH:
And those four young fellas with the measuring tape stopped coming around. So. Who's riding, Boone?

Silence. Joss looks from Dutch to Mack. Tito has stopped moving.

Mack doesn't answer right away. He looks at the drawing a long moment, really looks at it, like he's seeing it for the first time, doing arithmetic nobody taught him.

Then he looks around the table, one face at a time, and says it plain.

MACK:
So. You gentlemen want to go to the Moon?

Joss sits down on a sawhorse without checking it's there.

JOSS:
Wait. WAIT.

MACK:
The mission flies July first no matter what this building does. Six crates go up empty and six flags come down. Or four crates go up full. That's the whole choice. There isn't a third thing.

GUNNY:
And if this room says no?

MACK:
Then six crates fly empty, and I lose track of some scrap, and we all went to a lot of trouble over a carousel.

Quiet. The stove has no fire in it tonight, and nobody moves to light one.

Stitch gets up, walks to the open crate, and looks into the couch a moment. Then he climbs in, lies back, and sets his hat on his chest.

STITCH:
Snug.

Gunny crosses to the gear shelf and starts counting scrubber cartridges into ranks of four, marking the shelf edge with a grease pencil.

GUNNY:
Well. Now what do they take from us — cancel my Medicare on the Moon?

Dutch squares his pad on the drawing.

DUTCH:
The spec holds. I sized it.

Every face turns to Cricket, last.

Cricket looks at the crate a long moment. Then he walks over to it, sits down on the edge of it, and starts unlacing his boots.

CRICKET:
Somebody time me getting in. We'll want a number.

Tito comes over and raps the crate wall twice with one knuckle.

TITO:
(quiet)
She'll hold.

MACK:
(quiet, and for the first time all night, not selling anything)
You understand there's no backing out once you're up there. Bad heart at four g's, your age, no doctor closer than a quarter million miles.

GUNNY:
(not unkindly)
Boone, I've buried better men than me for worse reasons than this. Sit down or go home. Either's fine. Quit standing there doing arithmetic on our behalf.

A beat. Mack sits. Takes out his pen.

JOSS:
You're all insane. What do you need from me?

MACK:
The build order changes Monday. Nothing else does.

He takes out the pocket notebook, writes one line, and puts it away.

CUT TO:
